Interfacing: All these mesmerizing machines, just waiting to be plugged back in and played.
You: Kim 'Pinball' Kitsuragi, AKA Kimball?
Encyclopedia: Exactly. That's what he's known as. His reputation proceeds him!
You: "How did you..."

Kim Kitsuragi: He puts his glasses back on. "Fine. I was a juvenile police officer -- for over 15 years. It's how I started out in the RCM. Once I had to infiltrate a pinball ring. As you do -- when you're a juvie cop."
You: I'm not gonna talk to him about that.
You: "You're Kim 'Pinball' Kitsuragi."
You: "Hey, Kimball."
Kim Kitsuragi: "It is *lame*."
You: "Then why are you called Pinball?"
Kim Kitsuragi: "Not only to you -- I am *Lieutenant Kitsuragi* to everyone." He nods. "Now -- we really need to continue our sweep of what appears to be a secret path through the Whirling."
Kim Kitsuragi: "No. You're *gonna* call me Lieutenant Kitsuragi -- or on rare occasions 'Kim', because it's shorter." He nods. "Let's go."
Volition: Any plan to call him Pinball or Kimball is immediately wiped from your neocortex, as if with some sort of mind altering device. It is simply not going to happen.
You: "Let's move on then." [Finish thought.]
Encyclopedia: Of course, of course. Just something that swam to the surface. Go on, do real police work. This isn't a pinball mystery.
Suggestion: He also really doesn't want to talk about it.
You: "I'm gonna call you Pinball now."
Kim Kitsuragi: "It's best if *you* handle the juvenile delinquents," he nods.
You: "You're Lieutenant Kitsuragi to me."
You: "Don't worry, I'll keep calling you Kim."
You: "I'm gonna call you *Kimball* now."

You: "Wait, so *that's* why you didn't talk to Cuno."

Kim Kitsuragi: "Okay." He thinks for a moment. "I don't like pinball because I had to learn to play it for an undercover job at a pinball ring. And it's a lame, boring, and unchallenging game -- there. We can move on now."
Encyclopedia: You still feel he's holding out on Seolite pinball tricks, but fine. Explore on then.

You: [Discard thought.]
Kim Kitsuragi: "So *now* he remembers..." He looks at you in the silence of the workshop -- then takes his glasses off and cleans them.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Fine. I'm Kim 'Pinball' Kitsuragi." he puts them back on. "AKA The Kimball. You remembered -- congratulations."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Wonderful. He *only* remembers hearing about the *pinball policeman*."

Encyclopedia: It's strange that he doesn't like pinball. Kim here is a Seolite. His people are incredibly dextrous, and they all *love* pinball. Matter of fact...
Volition: Super. Tip-top! This went pretty well all things considered.
Kim Kitsuragi: "I am not *called* Pinball. It was used to taunt me -- a long time ago. *Before* I became a homicide detective. And got my lieutenancy."
You: "No matter. This is a failure. I'm failing and I'm going to stop."

Kim Kitsuragi: "Okay." He thinks for a moment. "I don't like pinball because I had to learn to play it for an undercover job at a pinball ring. And it's a lame, boring, and unchallenging game -- there. We can move on now."

Kim Kitsuragi: "But even *I* know that they don't play pinball. They have a rigid class society, and a punitive justice system..." He looks around. "We should continue with our exploration of this place. It doesn't matter."
You: "So you're not all, like, pinball aces? Because I could swear I know you are."
You: "Okay."
Kim Kitsuragi: "No. *They're* not -- let's move on. There's more to this place than pinball machines."

Encyclopedia: Deora was one of the three *Crown Cities* of the Dolorian era, on the Mundi isola -- the others being Rheasilvia and Advesperascit. This theme is all about early airships and beautiful, sad, pearl-laden women. It's quite nice actually.
Kim Kitsuragi: "No."
Kim Kitsuragi: "You can't *fire* them up, they're broken. Only that one machine in the main hall works. The Royalist Pinball." He looks away.
Half Light: What a dumb name -- Royalist Pinball. If they weren't broken, he would kick one of these machines about now.

Kim Kitsuragi: "Lieutenant Kitsuragi is good too." He nods. "Now -- we really need to continue our sweep of what appears to be a secret path through the Whirling."
You: "Wait, but I still can't remember anything *else*."
Kim Kitsuragi: "End of story."
You: "You were a juvie cop for 15 years?"
You: "What about that other one -- the Franconigerian Ball. Wanna play that?"
You: "Hey, didn't you guys, like, *invent* pinball?"
Volition: Stop.
You: "You know -- Seol guys. Massive pinball people."

Kim Kitsuragi: "Unbelievably," he nods. "To do that I needed to become a... *pinball champion*. I trained for nine months. The job was successful and I was moved out of the juvenile wing -- to homicide."
Empathy: So that's why he doesn't want to talk to Cuno. Trauma-and-Stressor Disorder from being a juvie cop.
Interfacing: Feels like it might jump back to life any moment, the lights illuminating the white robed woman.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Us *guys*?"
Kim Kitsuragi: "What?"
You: "Lame."
You: "Sounds like you don't enjoy pinball, Kim."
You: "What's 'White Deora'?"
You: "How about we fire one of these bad boys up and play some ball?"
Kim Kitsuragi: "No, I love it -- I love pinball. Who doesn't love pinball? Let's move on."
Drama: He doesn't.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Seol is an *extremely* protectionist isola, inaccessible to the rest of mankind. As it has been for over a thousand years. I have no special knowledge of them, despite my heritage."
Kim Kitsuragi: "That time is over now." He looks at the pinball machine and breathes in. "I was already a 38 year old man. It was unbecoming. As was playing pinball."
You: "Okay."
Kim Kitsuragi: "It was not okay. I needed to become a... *pinball champion*." He shudders. "I trained for 9 months. The job was successful and I was moved out of the juvenile wing -- to homicide."
Kim Kitsuragi: "No human being should. It is a game that requires no skill and a childlike affinity to flashing lights. And to *fantastique*, science fiction, and historic romance franchises."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Some kind of..." He looks around, thinking. "Inane pinball theme -- probably related to Messina during the Dolorian age. The *history themes* are the worst."
